ackend for both. This privileged position is justified given ESPN=E2=80=99s=
 preponderance of sports rights, and it also fits what I believe to be Disn=
ey=E2=80=99s strategy with ESPN. From a November 2023 Update ( https://stra=
techery.com/2023/disney-earnings-disney-3-0-streaming-and-sports/?access_to=
ken=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsI=
nR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJ=
IS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZX=
J5LmNvbS8yMDIzL2Rpc25leS1lYXJuaW5ncy1kaXNuZXktMy0wLXN0cmVhbWluZy1hbmQtc3Bvc=
nRzLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzA5OTA1NTk2LCJpYXQiOjE3MDczMTM1OTYsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8v=
YXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmV=
hZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOG=
pnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.Yi5EHs0ASU4vr4R_gb36lOCXvWm5SH7u=
5miZNx5ZJHz0Fc66bUKRUtxJJGRoQfkxdKChdA0M83sqPS2MYmi5vWKdWLOxUGd8F0KDbnFxxzY=
vm-1GRu_V2GwX4r_pOOQIMDT9DCORbExVp4TQG74JSQAz5LlR4LpG9GVH9oV0bLH9g1FsQYT7mP=
CWR0QcsP8_J6m5UR7TaaSAv-zQD305QHQdSFOvIt7qoo8a7R4uk7VpavBPfopqEcBvzAA4FR27K=
lb9UMLPpChruPjpaRZPJjplg1zW4OT4R_F5wCCJzTZwJaUiESX4p7JjBA-LI3dQgvrWwsW4LJHN=
LflEt1qn5w ) :

If you want to build a broad-based advertising business across your streami=
ng platforms then I think sports is very useful. It is the biggest draw for=
 advertisers, and still operates at a much larger scale than any other adve=
rtising-supported medium in the world. Fast forward a few years, when ESPN =
is available as a streaming service, and it is going to be a service that e=
very advertiser works with; it will be an obvious step, then, to extend adv=
ertising to Disney=E2=80=99s general entertainment and Disney+ content, as =
well. After all, it=E2=80=99s the same platform, with the same targeting, t=
hat you=E2=80=99re using anyway.

This also explains why Disney is making sports into its own reporting segme=
nt and is seeking external partnerships: sure, a spin-off is an option, but=
 I think the real goal is to capture the value of bundling with sports and,=
 more importantly, of having a common advertising platform, while ensuring =
that Disney keeps the upside of that linkage (which will be realized in ad =
revenue on its non-sports services). In that sense I=E2=80=99m actually not=
 sure how valuable a partnership would be for either tech companies or spor=
ts leagues, even if the allure for Disney is clear.

That skepticism about tech companies and sports leagues holds; Warner Bros.=
 Discover, on the other hand, still has lots of debt to service, and must b=
e feeling nervous about the rapidly shrinking bundle and its dependence on =
traditional affiliate revenue. If Disney helps it pay the bills for sports =
rights that are not particularly profitable in isolation, but which still p=
rop up other parts of their business, than that may be enough.

That leaves Fox, who is in perhaps the most interesting position of any of =
the major entertainment companies. Fox wisely realized that it would be foo=
lish to try and build its own streaming service, and instead sold its gener=
al entertainment assets (21st Century Fox) to Disney; the company would ins=
tead double-down on live, with its two most important tent posts being the =
Fox broadcasting network and Fox News. This strategy was, in my estimation,=
 sound, but for the fact that the cable bundle has disintegrated far faster=
 than Fox probably expected. I wrote in an Update last year ( https://strat=
echery.com/2023/max-gets-sports-the-fox-linchpin-disneys-taylor-swift-era-c=
onfirmed/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3=
Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5v=
bmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHR=
wczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIzL21heC1nZXRzLXNwb3J0cy10aGUtZm94LWxpbmNocG=
luLWRpc25leXMtdGF5bG9yLXN3aWZ0LWVyYS1jb25maXJtZWQvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MDk5MDU1O=
TYsImlhdCI6MTcwNzMxMzU5NiwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29h=
dXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk=
6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIj=
oiYWNjZXNzIn0.QYX4WjeAnfERWlpE75cX-X9NCxjNIqUy38ilByABjYRzmUX_DGJHui_WGO9l_=
rpUjEuUrvADWkWvTM99iSYv1R2DK0kNFo90J9Q0jxYle8hHleprNwm5OEkhqeiBZzbIQjDt6BvH=
XUWbdAC-fpCB7k9Hmod22S_xH9cMTcGQ6WFgzuwaocU7NUfftVfJCK2FzCU1uLBYDBQS1efhIBe=
e6jurdeCY7KM64zGBa477Bj6-0LoZutIKGAHIyTaYo4rTIDfQPwoNbSU4I7lVbOf_MSOkmvax42=
2oU68Zc8XTH8twjrDyqlenoS0CSpgeTHGOUnIdj9EtEHb_zYJNLr51wA ) :

Keep in mind that the real moneymaker for Fox is retransmission fees (for F=
ox) and affiliate fees (primarily for Fox News); retransmission fees don=E2=
=80=99t exist if viewers use an antenna, and Fox News is the epitome of a c=
hannel that captures affiliate fees from the entire bundle base because its=
 fans will change their TV service to get it. Of course Charter just showed=
 the increased fragility of that strategy, but the broader point is that ke=
eping the bundle viable is still Fox=E2=80=99s number one priority; if ESPN=
 isn=E2=80=99t going to lend a hand then it may fall on Murdoch to make a b=
ig sports deal that doesn=E2=80=99t make sense individually but is good for=
 the company as a whole, just like his father did with the NFL thirty years=
 ago.

What I was hinting at with that last sentence was the NBA, but Murdoch clea=
rly isn=E2=80=99t interested; instead the company will seek to recoup some =
of what it spends on sports rights via this streaming service.

Frankly, I find this the least compelling for Fox. On one hand, this is a s=
hort-term win: Fox doesn=E2=80=99t have any real streaming service to speak=
 of, so piggy-backing on this effort keeps their sports rights viable. On t=
he other hand, sports rights tend to be very poor investments in-and-of-the=
mselves: they are best leveraged in service of something else, like Rupert =
Murdoch=E2=80=99s push to make Fox into a nationwide broadcasting network v=
ia the NFL, or Disney=E2=80=99s attempt to boot-up an at-scale advertising =
network via ads in games. Fox, though, doesn=E2=80=99t have any auxiliary b=
usinesses that benefit from this bundle: they just hasten the demise of the=
ir actual moneymaker.

The other services worth considering in this analysis are Peacock and Param=
ount+, which matter for the simple reason that they have NFL games. Frankly=
, I take their lack of inclusion as further evidence that their executives =
have no idea what they are doing: both services are subscale, provide minim=
al subscriber promise of ongoing content to justify staying subscribed mont=
h-over-month, and, in the case of Peacock, are in direct conflict with a ke=
y revenue driver for their parent company. The NFL, meanwhile, is not only =
the most ruthless in extracting every bit of value it provides from its con=
tracts (necessitating orthogonal strategies like Fox in the 1990s), but is =
also only on for half the year: are Peacock and Paramount+ simply going to =
accept that most of their customers will churn every single year for half t=
he year?

So, about those customers: the most important takeaway is one I noted after=
 the launch of Max=E2=80=99s sports tier ( https://stratechery.com/2023/max=
-gets-sports-the-fox-linchpin-disneys-taylor-swift-era-confirmed/?access_to=
